<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1014,1041]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,1015,1041]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[361,582,1016,1043]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa tahẚtẚensẚs</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[588,763,1015,1041]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. et sp. nov.</emphasis>
by original designation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="264" pageNumber="265" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="264.[151,1437,690,1113]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1051,1077]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Etymology.</emphasis>
In Greek mythology, 
<emphasis box="[580,678,1052,1079]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa</emphasis>
was a princess of the giants, daughter of the giant king Porphyrion. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="264" pageNumber="265" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="264.[151,1437,1159,1619]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,1159,1185]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Remarks.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[276,373,1160,1187]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[382,489,1159,1185]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
is undoubtedly closely related to 
<emphasis box="[875,1032,1160,1187]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Mçnnẚçtẚcçpa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1041,1147,1159,1185]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
In both genera, the mandible forms a powerful claw, the antenna is digitiform and distinctly segmented, and the maxillule is bilobed. However, several significant features prevent its 
<typeStatus box="[696,744,1231,1257]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">type</typeStatus>
species from being accommodated within 
<emphasis box="[1223,1380,1232,1259]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Mçnnẚçtẚcçpa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
The most significant diagnostic feature of the new genus is found in the swimming legs, which consist of a small, free exopod and an elongate, unsegmented protopod-endopod complex. Within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aurivillius" authorityYear="1885" box="[1176,1325,1303,1329]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Enteropsidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Enteropsidae</taxonomicName>
, a similar form of swimming legs is present in 
<emphasis box="[578,765,1339,1367]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">iequerrea canuẚ</emphasis>
Illg &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dudley, P. L." box="[854,1006,1339,1365]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref142450" refString="Illg, P. L. &amp; Dudley, P. L. (1980) The family Ascidicolidae and its subfamilies (Copepoda, Cyclopoida), with descriptions of new species. Memc ẚres du Museum kat ẚcnal d'e ẚstcẚre katurelleI mar ẚs, Serie A, Zoologie, 117, 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="1980">
<collectingRegion box="[854,938,1339,1365]" country="United Kingdom" name="Dudley" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Dudley</collectingRegion>
, 1980
</bibRefCitation>
(Illg &amp; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dudley, P. L." box="[1104,1261,1339,1365]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" pagination="1 - 192" refId="ref142450" refString="Illg, P. L. &amp; Dudley, P. L. (1980) The family Ascidicolidae and its subfamilies (Copepoda, Cyclopoida), with descriptions of new species. Memc ẚres du Museum kat ẚcnal d'e ẚstcẚre katurelleI mar ẚs, Serie A, Zoologie, 117, 1 - 192." type="journal article" year="1980">
<collectingRegion box="[1104,1188,1339,1365]" country="United Kingdom" name="Dudley" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Dudley</collectingRegion>
, 1980
</bibRefCitation>
), but the genus 
<emphasis box="[151,267,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">iequerrea</emphasis>
can be clearly differentiated from 
<emphasis box="[656,754,1376,1403]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[762,867,1375,1401]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
by the lack of antennae and by the structure of the mouthparts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="264.[151,1437,1159,1619]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
The body of female 
<emphasis box="[429,526,1448,1475]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[535,640,1447,1473]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
is clearly divisible into prosome and urosome, and this can be considered as a diagnostic feature of the genus, because the prosome-urosome division is obscured by fusion of the fourth and fifth pedigerous somites in all known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aurivillius" authorityYear="1885" box="[743,893,1519,1545]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Enteropsidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Enteropsidae</taxonomicName>
. The caudal rami are also distinctive in 
<emphasis box="[1338,1436,1520,1547]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">merẚbçẚa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,255,1555,1581]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
; they are elongate and unarmed, which differs from the broad caudal ramus, uniformly armed with 1 major and several vestigial setae in known species of 
<emphasis box="[680,837,1592,1619]" italics="true" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">Mçnnẚçtẚcçpa</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[844,949,1591,1617]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">gen. nov.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
